carrying Chinese goods have started to move towards the Himalayan country. Till Thursday, 88 trucks loaded with garments, electronic items, shoes and slippers, food items among others crossed the Sino-Nepali Friendship Bridge.\",\"time\":1461574901},{\"contentid\":105052,\"icon\":\"\",\"iconsrc\":\"\",\"title\":\"CHINA-FUNDED RAILWAY TO BENEFIT KENYA\",\"color\":\"\",\"url\":\"http:\\/\\/db.silkroad.news.cn\\/en\\/2016\\/0425\\/105052.shtml\",\"subtitle\":\"\",\"suburl\":\"\",\"thumb\":\"http:\\/\\/upload.db.silkroad.news.cn\\/2016\\/0425\\/1461569469663.jpg\",\"description\":\"China has funded the building of a key rail line in Kenya. While the construction is in full-swing, people have started to expect the changes brought by the new rail line. According to the railway builder, China Road and Bridge Corporation (CRBC), the construction has reached a critical phase. And the Standard Gauge Railway (SGR) will cut travel time between Nairobi and Mombasa by half. During the construction, many young Kenyan people are working together with experienced Chinese workers, which is expected to help with their own technical skills.\",\"time\":1461574542},{\"contentid\":105053,\"icon\":\"\",\"iconsrc\":\"\",\"title\":\"CHINESE CENTRAL BANK\'S TOP TASKS FOR 2016\",\"color\":\"\",\"url\":\"http:\\/\\/db.silkroad.news.cn\\/en\\/2016\\/0425\\/105053.shtml\",\"subtitle\":\"\",\"suburl\":\"\",\"thumb\":\"http:\\/\\/upload.db.silkroad.news.cn\\/2016\\/0425\\/1461569551973.jpg\",\"description\":\"China\'s central bank has unveiled its prioritized tasks for 2016. It outlines a monetary support policy framework, as well as priorities and economic development goals. The People\'s Bank of China said monetary policy will help slash overcapacity, cut stockpiles, reduce leverage, lower costs of doing business and fix shortcomings, with a focus on reducing steel and coal overcapacity. The central bank will continue to give differentiated housing loan policy to different regions based on their market conditions.\",\"time\":1461574250},{\"contentid\":104917,\"icon\":\"\",\"iconsrc\":\"\",\"title\":\"GERMAN KEEPS GROWTH FORECAST AT 1.7 PCT  \",\"color\":\"\",\"url\":\"http:\\/\\/db.silkroad.news.cn\\/en\\/2016\\/0422\\/104917.shtml\",\"subtitle\":\"\",\"suburl\":\"\",\"thumb\":\"http:\\/\\/upload.db.silkroad.news.cn\\/2016\\/0422\\/1461299099297.jpg\",\"description\":\"    The German government kept its 2016 growth forecast at 1.7 percent on Wednesday, unchanged from its earlier prediction, saying strong domestic economy would offset losses in exports.\\n    German Federal Economy Ministry said following a 1.7 percent growth in 2015, the German economy would expand at the same rate this year.\",\"time\":1461317858}]',NULL,NULL,NULL,'<ul class=\"pic1-ul\">\n<!--{loop $data $k $r}-->\n  <li><a href=\"{$r[url]}\" target=\"_blank\">\n    	<img src=\" {thumb($r[thumb],150,113,1,null,null)}\" width=\"150\"\n                                     height=\"113\" /></a>\n        <h3><a href=\"{$r[url]}\" target=\"_blank\">{str_cut($r[title], 45, \'\')}</a></h3>\n</li>\n<!--{/loop}-->\n</ul>\n\n','html',NULL,4,0,0,'{\"system_fields\":{\"contentid\":{\"checked\":\"1\",\"func\":\"intval\"},\"title\":{\"checked\":\"1\",\"required\":\"1\",\"min_length\":\"\",\"max_length\":\"\"},\"url\":{\"checked\":\"1\"},\"color\":{\"checked\":\"1\"},\"icon\":{\"checked\":\"1\"},\"iconsrc\":{\"checked\":\"1\"},\"subtitle\":{\"checked\":\"1\",\"min_length\":\"\",\"max_length\":\"\"},\"suburl\":{\"checked\":\"1\"},\"thumb\":{\"checked\":\"1\",\"width\":\"\",\"height\":\"\"},\"description\":{\"checked\":\"1\",\"min_length\":\"\",\"max_length\":\"\"},\"time\":{\"checked\":\"1\",\"func\":\"section_fields_strtotime\"}},\"custom_fields\":{\"text\":[],\"name\":[]}}',1476433885,1476433885,0,0,1461634013,3,1457493461,5,'',1,0,'section/list.html',0,10),(321,47,'push','列表页轮播图','[]','[{\"contentid\":102140,\"icon\":\"\",\"iconsrc\":\"\",\"title\":\"CHINA SETS NEW ONLINE IMPORT TAX RULES\",\"color\":\"\",\"url\":\"http:\\/\\/db.silkroad.news.cn\\/en-db\\/2016\\/0329\\/102140.shtml\",\"subtitle\":\"\",\"suburl\":\"\",\"thumb\":\"http:\\/\\/upload.db.silkroad.news.cn\\/2016\\/0328\\/1459148633429.jpg\",\"description\":\"China will change the tax rules on online retail goods from April 8 to level the playing field for e-commerce platforms and traditional retailers and importers.\\n\\nRetail goods purchased online will no longer be classified as \\\"parcels,\\\" which enjoy a \\\"parcel tax\\\" rate, lower than that on other imported goods.\\n\\nThe Ministry of Finance (MOF) said online purchases from overseas will be charged in the same way as any other imported goods.\\n\\nChina levies parcel tax on imported goods worth less than 1,000 yuan, and the rates is mostly 10 percent. \\n\\nTaxes under 50 yuan are waived. \\n\\nAs demand for overseas goods grows, online purchasing agents have taken advantage of parcel tax and used new methods such as repackaging and mailing products separately to avoid tax.\\n\\nThe new policy only allows a maximum of 2,000 yuan per single cross-border transaction and a maximum of 20,000 yuan per person per year. \\n\\nThe MOF said goods that exceed these limits will be levied the full tax for general trade.\\n\\nAccording to a 2015 survey by Amazon China on online imports, most buyers are under 35 and around 90 percent have a college education. More than half earn more than 5,000 yuan per month. \\n\\nThe new policy will speed up customs clearance so consumers will receive most orders from overseas within two weeks, instead of the current two months.\\n\\nCross-border e-commerce has been booming in China. \\n\\nThe Ministry of Commerce predicted the volume of cross-border e-commerce in 2016 will reach 6.5 trillion yuan and will soon account for 20 percent of China\'s foreign trade.\\n\",\"time\":1459213966},{\"contentid\":102145,\"icon\":\"\",\"iconsrc\":\"\",\"title\":\"NW CHINA REGULAR CARGO TRAIN CONNECTS WITH KAZAKHSTAN\",\"color\":\"\",\"url\":\"http:\\/\\/db.silkroad.news.cn\\/en-db\\/2016\\/0328\\/102145.shtml\",\"subtitle\":\"\",\"suburl\":\"\",\"thumb\":\"http:\\/\\/upload.db.silkroad.news.cn\\/2016\\/0328\\/1459148699514.jpg\",\"description\":\"A cargo train arrived at northwest China\'s Xi\'an city on last Saturday, carrying 2,000 tonnes of organic cooking oil imported from Kazakhstan. This marks the successful operation of the first regular cargo service between the two countries. Named the Chang\'an Train, the cargo train loaded with 1,000 tonnes of sunflower seed oil and 1,000 tonnes of rapeseed oil, set off from Almaty of Kazakhstan on Monday. The journey is the first regular cargo service between Kazakhstan and china. The train started to run between Xi\'an and Almaty at the end of 2013, carrying cargo from China to central Asia, but previously was empty or carried few goods on its return. It usually takes six days to complete the 3,860-km journey. So far, the train has transported a total of more than 280,000 tonnes of goods to central Asia with a gross export value of about 290 million U.S. dollars.\",\"time\":1459155480},{\"contentid\":101323,\"icon\":\"\",\"iconsrc\":\"\",\"title\":\"CHINESE INVESTMENT IN INDIA GOES NORTHWARD\",\"color\":\"\",\"url\":\"http:\\/\\/db.silkroad.news.cn\\/en-db\\/2016\\/0325\\/101323.shtml\",\"subtitle\":\"\",\"suburl\":\"\",\"thumb\":\"http:\\/\\/upload.db.silkroad.news.cn\\/2016\\/0323\\/1458719320199.jpg\",\"description\":\"India has emerged as one of the most sought after destinations for foreign investment in recent years. Over the 15 months ended in December 2015, foreign direct investment in the country has gone-up by 29 percent. \\n\\nFrom Foxconn to General Motors, global giants are making a beeline to invest in India. \\n\\nChinese companies have also intensified their efforts in order to invest in the world\'s fastest growing large economy in last couple of years as India under new regime has opened its doors for Chinese investors.\\n\\nLiuGong, one of the World\'s top-20 construction equipment manufacturers made its India debut in 2002. Going by its successful run, the Chinese company set-up its first manufacturing facility in the country in 2009 and started manufacturing its products in India itself. Despite initial hiccups in the wake of global economic slowdown, LiuGong\'s business from India has gone-up manifold. \\n\\nThe company which has 98 percent Indians in its staff in the country has grown up by 30 percent annually since 2011, the year when the company\'s sales in India started picking up. For their exponential growth in India, LiuGong officials give credit to ever-strengthening relations between India and China.\\n\\nAs the business between India and China has been going northward, travel exchanges have also gone-up between the two of the largest Asian economies. \\n\\nGuangzhou-based China Southern Airlines started its India operations in 2007 with just three flights a week from New Delhi to Guangzhou. Now, the company is operating 14 flights per week on the same route. The company officials claim to have doubled its India business in last five years. \\n\\nThe aviation company is now demanding the Indian government to increase quota for Chinese airlines so that they can start operating flights from other Indian cities as well. \\n\\nWhile highlighting the huge growth potential of Indian market, General Manager of China Southern Airlines\' India operations Chen Yongguang shares his India experience.  \\n\\nCorporations around the world now view India as a place where the future growth is expected to arise. The favourable demography and rising disposable incomes drive India\'s consumer market. \\n\\nA latest report by McKinsey Global Institute expects Indian average household incomes to triple over the next two decades, making India the world\'s fifth largest consumer economy by 2025. \\n\\nThe country continues to grab the top spot in Nielsen\'s global consumer confidence survey for last two years. \\n\\nRealising the potential, Chinese real estate major Wanda has recently announced to invest nearly 10 billion dollars in India. This is being termed as the biggest investment from a Chinese company in India, so far. \\n\\nThis comes close on the heels of a spate of investment that has come into various sectors in India from China last year. From e-commerce giant Alibaba to cab services provider Didi Kuaidi to finance firms such as Hillhouse Capital - Chinese companies are aggressively acquiring stakes in Indian companies to make their presence felt in Asia\'s third largest economy. \\n\\nIndian Parliament member and leader of the country\'s ruling BJP Tarun Vijay has great hopes for India-China relations to improve further as he expects more investment to find its way into India from China.\\n\\nChinese investment trickled down in India between 2000 and 2015 was around 1.2 billion dollars. It was just 0.47 percent of the total foreign direct investment inflow in the country. \\n\\nIn 2015, about a hundred Chinese companies have vowed to invest in India, taking the total Chinese investment in India to over 3 billion dollars. \\n\",\"time\":1458870860},{\"contentid\":101319,\"icon\":\"\",\"iconsrc\":\"\",\"title\":\"CHINA RAILWAY GROUP INVESTS $2BN IN MALAYSIA\",\"color\":\"\",\"url\":\"http:\\/\\/db.silkroad.news.cn\\/en-db\\/2016\\/0325\\/101319.shtml\",\"subtitle\":\"\",\"suburl\":\"\",\"thumb\":\"http:\\/\\/upload.db.silkroad.news.cn\\/2016\\/0323\\/1458719235738.jpg\",\"description\":\"China Railway Group Limited (CREC) announces a 2 billion-U.S. dollar investment in Malaysia with an eye on further expansion into the Southeast Asian market.\\n\\nMonday\'s announcement came three months after CREC\'s successful bid with its Malaysian joint-venture partner in December to acquire 60 percent of the equity in the Bandar Malaysia project.\\n\\nStatically located about 7 km from the Kuala Lumpur city center, Bandar Malaysia would also serve as the terminal for the proposed high-speed railway linking the Malaysian capital and Singapore. \\n\\nAccording to CREC, it would consolidate all its current regional businesses and operations once its new headquarters is up and running.\\n\",\"time\":1458870860},{\"contentid\":101311,\"icon\":\"\",\"iconsrc\":\"\",\"title\":\"VIETNAM\'S ECONOMY SET TO GROW 6.5-7% IN 5 YEARS\",\"color\":\"\",\"url\":\"http:\\/\\/db.silkroad.news.cn\\/en-db\\/2016\\/0325\\/101311.shtml\",\"subtitle\":\"\",\"suburl\":\"\",\"thumb\":\"http:\\/\\/upload.db.silkroad.news.cn\\/2016\\/0323\\/1458718487561.jpg\",\"description\":\"Vietnam\'s economic growth target is expected to range from 6.5 to 7 percent in the five years.\\n\\nThat\'s according to the report released at the 11th session of the 13th National Assembly of Vietnam, which kicked off in capital Hanoi on Monday.\\n\\nVietnam\'s  average gross domestic product (GDP) growth during 2011-2015 period hit 5.91 percent annually.\\n\\nThe country\'s GDP reached 193.4 billion U.S. dollars in 2015, with GDP per capita being 2,109 U.S. dollars.\\n\\nSpecifically, during the 2011-2015 period, the sector of industry, construction witnessed average growth of 6.9 percent annually. Average growth of agriculture hit 3 percent each year while the service expanded at 6.3 percent annually on average. While total retail sales of goods and services increased 14.1 percent each year.\\n\\nDuring the session, the five-year socio-economic development plan during 2016-2020 period will be approved.\\n\\nThe report on the national socio-economic development plan for 2016-2020 said by 2020, average GDP per capita will stay at about 3,200-3,500 USD and State budget overspending is expected at around 4 percent. \\n\\nThe session is scheduled to last till April 12. \",\"time\":1458870860},{\"contentid\":101413,\"icon\":\"\",\"iconsrc\":\"\",\"title\":\"EXPERT ON RISING HOUSING PRICES\",\"color\":\"\",\"url\":\"http:\\/\\/db.silkroad.news.cn\\/en-db\\/2016\\/0325\\/101413.shtml\",\"subtitle\":\"\",\"suburl\":\"\",\"thumb\":\"http:\\/\\/upload.db.silkroad.news.cn\\/2016\\/0324\\/1458801885442.jpg\",\"description\":\"The latest data from National Bureau of Statistics (NBS) show that China\'s housing market continues to warm in February, with more than half of surveyed major cities reporting month-on-month rises in new home prices.\\n   \\nOf the 70 large and medium-sized cities surveyed in February, new home prices climbed month on month in 47, up from 38 the previous month. Meanwhile, 15 reported month-on-month price declines, down from 24 in January.\\n\\nCEO of Sino-Ocean Real Estate, one of the largest real estate groups in China, says the rises have nothing to do with so-called housing bubble.\\n\\nOn a yearly basis, 32 cities across China posted new-home price increases and 37 reported decreases, compared with 25 and 45 in January.\\n   \\nNew-home prices soared 57.8 percent year on year in the southern city of Shenzhen, the sharpest increase, followed by Shanghai and Beijing. \\n\\nThe northeastern city of Dandong registered the steepest price decline, dropping by 3.9 percent.\",\"time\":1458870859}]',NULL,NULL,NULL,'<!--{loop $data $k $r}-->\n <li>\n <a href=\"javascript:;\" hidefocus=\"true\"><img src=\"{thumb($r[thumb])}\" width=\"105\" height=\"80\" alt=\"{$r[title]}\"/></a>\n\n <p>\n     <label class=\"tit-h4\"><a href=\"{$r[url]}\" target=\"_blank\">{$r[title]}</a></label>\n     <em>{date(\'Y-m-d H:i\')}</em>\n     <span>{$r[description]}</span>\n </p>\n <i title=\"img\">{thumb($r[thumb])}</i>\n</li>\n<!--{/loop}-->\n','html',NULL,8,0,0,'{\"system_fields\":{\"contentid\":{\"checked\":\"1\",\"func\":\"intval\"},\"title\":{\"checked\":\"1\",\"required\":\"1\",\"min_length\":\"\",\"max_length\":\"\"},\"url\":{\"checked\":\"1\"},\"color\":{\"checked\":\"1\"},\"icon\":{\"checked\":\"1\"},\"iconsrc\":{\"checked\":\"1\"},\"subtitle\":{\"checked\":\"1\",\"min_length\":\"\",\"max_length\":\"\"},\"suburl\":{\"checked\":\"1\"},\"thu